revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=June 2017}} The '''BFI TV 100''' is a list compiled in 2000 by the [[British Film Institute]] (BFI), chosen by a poll of industry professionals{{huh|date=April 2018}}, to determine what were the greatest [[United Kingdom|British]] television programmes of any genre to have been screened.
==Selection and criteria== [[File:BBC TV Centre.jpg|thumb|right|The [[BBC]] produced 70 of the 100 programmes on the list.]] [[File:Granada TV.jpg|thumb|right|[[Granada Television]] produced 7 of the 100 programmes on list - the largest by a commercial broadcaster.]] Initially, a 'big list' of 650 programmes was drawn up by BFI personnel, and this provisional list was then distributed to 1,600 television industry professionals in the UK,<ref name=Barnes/> who were each given 30 votes. The listing was split into six categories: Single Dramas, Drama Series and Serials, Comedy and Variety, Factual, Children's / Youth, and Lifestyle & Light Entertainment. Each voter was required to cast a minimum of three votes in every category. News stories were mostly excluded, with exceptions such as the coverage of the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], on the basis that it would be impossible to determine whether it was the coverage or the news itself that made them important. Sport was excluded for similar reasons, and also because many events such as the [[Football World Cup 1966|1966 World Cup]], while important to those in England, would not necessarily matter to those in other areas of the United Kingdom.
Some programmes are represented on the list by an entire series. For some series, such as the anthology ''[[The Wednesday Play]]'' and current affairs show ''[[This Week (Thames Television, UK)|This Week]]'', individual episodes are listed. Television programmes no longer existing in the archives were excluded from consideration.
The judges were also asked to name their top overseas programme; the winner was the US sitcom ''[[Frasier]]''.<ref name=Barnes/>
